05022nam a22005775i 9780226820996DE-B159720221205051307.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221205t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2022012505  a9780226820996  a(DE-B1597)642810  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHG4516b.C76 2022 4aHG4516 7aBUS0000002bisacsh1 aCrosthwaite, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInvested :bHow Three Centuries of Stock Market Advice Reshaped Our Money, Markets, and Minds /cPaul Crosthwaite, Nicky Marsh, Helen Paul, James Taylor, Peter Knight. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b15 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Three Centuries of Financial Advice -- tChapter 1. Making the Market (1720–1800) -- tChapter 2. Navigating the Market (1800–1870) -- tChapter 3. Playing the Market (1870–1910) -- tChapter 4. Chartists and Fundamentalists (1910–1950) -- tChapter 5. Domestic Budgets and Efficient Markets (1950–1990) -- tChapter 6. Gurus and Robots (1990–2020) -- tConclusion: Investing through the Crisis -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInvested examines the perennial and nefarious appeal of financial advice manuals. Who hasn’t wished for a surefire formula for riches and a ticket to the good life? For three centuries, investment advisers of all kinds, legit and otherwise, have guaranteed that they alone can illuminate the golden pathway to prosperity—despite strong evidence to the contrary. In fact, too often, they are singing a siren song of devastation. And yet we keep listening. Invested tells the story of how the genre of investment advice developed and grew in the United Kingdom and the United States, from its origins in the eighteenth century through today, as it saturates our world. The authors analyze centuries of books, TV shows, blogs, and more, all promising techniques for amateur investors to master the ways of the market: from Thomas Mortimer’s pathbreaking 1761 work, Every Man His Own Broker, through the Gilded Age explosion of sensationalist investment manuals, the early twentieth-century emergence of a vernacular financial science, and the more recent convergence of self-help and personal finance. Invested asks why, in the absence of evidence that such advice reliably works, guides to the stock market have remained perennially popular. The authors argue that the appeal of popular investment advice lies in its promise to level the playing field, giving outsiders the privileged information of insiders. As Invested persuasively shows, the fantasies sold by these writings are damaging and deceptive, peddling unrealistic visions of easy profits and the certainty of success, while trying to hide the fact that there is no formula for avoiding life’s economic uncertainties and calamities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aCapitalismxHistory. 0aFinance literaturezGreat BritainxHistory. 0aFinance literaturezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aInvestment advisorszGreat BritainxHistory. 0aInvestment advisorszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aInvestmentsxHistory. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  awealth, investment, stock market crash, recession, financial markets, nonfiction, rich, american dream, prosperity, profit, success, ambition, tv shows, television, personal finance, self-help, manuals, gilded age, every man his own broker, thomas mortimer, amateur investors, techniques, strategy, blogs, popular culture, class.1 aKnight, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMarsh, Nicky, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/voc